<p><b>What is the message of doubt?</b> As made evident by the title, Doubt is a play that examines how people deal with feelings of uncertainty and skepticism. Considering that the play takes place in a Catholic parish, the most obvious manifestation of doubt is the kind that arises when people question their religious faith.</p>
<p><b>What is the main idea or message of the parable?</b> According to the dictionary, parables are short allegorical stories designed to teach a truth, religious principle, or moral lesson. They are often engaging stories that contain few details but are ripe with meaning. Parables have a place in the tradition of Jewish storytelling.</p>
<p><b>What is the lesson of doubt by John Patrick Shanley?</b> The lesson we are supposed to learn from John Patrick Shanley's parable, Doubt a Parable, is that we should never be too sure of our beliefs. The play encourages us to always question our own certainties, because even those that seem the most certain can be wrong.</p>
