<p><b>What is the point of doubt?</b> Doubt helps us avoid acting on every passing idea which can prevent us from participating in certain types of risk. We should all cut ourselves some slack for how much we doubt.</p>
<p><b>What is the thesis of Doubt: A Parable?</b> In the play Doubt, a Parable written by John Patrick Shanley, explains how doubt can lead to certainty and how an individual assurance can lead back to doubt. The relationship between Father Flynn and Sister Aloysius is a back and forth conflict between certainty and doubt.</p>
<p><b>What is the purpose of doubt?</b> Doubt often represents a challenge to something that others have invested in. If someone derives his power or social standing from a belief that you challenge, take a guess what their response is going to be.</p>
<p><b>What is a parable message?</b> A parable is a tale that illustrates a moral lesson or ethical principle. Parables are concise, expressive and often appear in spiritual texts such as the Bible. Parables feature human characters and situations, distinguishing them from fables, which typically involve plants and animals.</p>